DANNY Jordaan has won the Safa presidential elections with a landslide at the Sandtopn Convention Centre. Jordaan retained the Safa president seat for the third term with 186 votes, while his challenger Ria Ledwaba came second with 27 votes. Safa Tshwane president Solly Mohlabeng got only eight votes. Breaking News: Dr Danny Jordaan retained his seat as South African Football Association (SAFA) President when he won by overwhelming majority at the Elective Congress on Saturday.Dr Jordaan polled 186 votes, Ria Ledwaba 27 votes and Solly Mohlabeng 8 votes As expected, Jordaan was overwhelming candidates to clinch the votes before the elections started with the NEC and regions in favour of him to continue. Others who were voting were Safa associate members. The IEC was the counting the votes, SunSport has been informed. Jordaan will serve as Safa head for a third term since being voted into power in 2013, stretching his tenure to at 13 years.The 2022 Elective Congress has been marred with attempts to have the courts postpone the event, however, interdict applications were thrown out in the past two weeks as various applicants were left unsuccessful in their hopes to stop the re-election of Jordaan. ALSO READ:Â Court rejects Ledwaba's application to stop Safa elections The new SAFA vice president is yet to be confirmed, while the National Executive Committee members are also expected to be confirmed before Congress is brought to a close. 